1 Learning Outcomes

  • Download and work with Census Bureau data

  • Create maps in R using Census Bureau data.

  • References:
    • tidycensus

    • The US Census Bureau has numerous location and other data sets on its site or with links to other authoritative sites.

  • Census Bureau

2 tidycensus Package

  • tidycensus allows users to interface with the US Census Bureau’s decennial Census and five-year American Community Survey APIs and return tidyverse-ready data frames, with the option for including simple feature geometry at various levels.
  • Install the tidycensus package using the console

  • Load the package

    library(tidycensus)
library(tidyverse)

#key_set("CENSUS_API_KEY_SECURE")

2.2 tidycensus Functions for the Decennial Census and the American Community Survey

  • There are two major functions implemented in tidycensus:
    • get_decennial() grants access to the 1990, 2000, and 2010 decennial US Census APIs, and
    • get_acs() grants access to the 5-year American Community Survey APIs.

  • See the help page

  • Let’s look at median gross rent by state in 1990:

    m90 <- get_decennial(geography = "state", variables = "H043A001", year = 1990, key = Sys.getenv("CENSUS_API_KEY"))
    ## Getting data from the 1990 decennial Census
    head(m90)

2.3 Searching for Variable Identifiers

  • Getting variables from the Census or ACS requires knowing the variable ID - and there are thousands of these IDs across the different Census files.
  • To rapidly search for variables, use the load_variables() function.
    • Two required arguments:
      • the year of the Census or end year of the ACS sample, and
      • the dataset - one of “sf1”, “sf3”, or “acs5”.
  • For ideal functionality, you may want to assign the result of this function to a variable, setting cache = TRUE to store the result on your computer for future access.
  • View and filter or use R to search the categories etc,,

  • The names for the same type of data may be different across files and years

    v17 <- load_variables(2017, "acs5", cache = TRUE)
categories <- enframe(sort(unique(str_extract(v17$concept,"^.{35}"))))

#View(v17)

2.3.1 Find the variable for median gross rent for the 2000 census in the sf3 file

  • use load_variables()

    c32000 <- load_variables(2000, "sf3", cache = TRUE)
#view(c32000) # use filters to find median gross rent
#median gross rent H063001

c32000 %>% 
  filter(str_detect(label, "^Median gross rent")) %>% 
  select(name, label)

3 Mapping with Census Data

3.1 Set up the environment with the required libraries for mapping

  • The tidycensus package makes it easier to work with census data - you need a census API key
  • The SimpleFeatures (sf) R package provides a standardized way to encode spatial vector data.
    • It binds to ‘GDAL’ for reading and writing data, to ‘GEOS’ for geometrical operations, and to ‘PROJ’ for projection conversions and datum transformations.
  • To save the census tract data between sessions set the option: options(tigris_use_cache = TRUE)
  • viridis color palettes are perceptually uniform and legible to colorblind individuals and in black and white.

    • viridis palettes are popular for data visualization, including for choropleth mapping.

      # install.packages for the following
library(tidyverse)
library(tidycensus)
library(tigris)
library(sf)
library(viridis) #a color palette
options(tigris_use_cache = TRUE)

3.2 Download Census Data with geography (simpler features) objects

  • See here for the possible levels

  • The following example gets median household income from the 2014-2018 ACS for census tracts for Baltimore City

    baltimore <- get_acs(state = "MD", county = "Baltimore City", geography = "tract", 
                  variables = "B19013_001", geometry = TRUE, key = Sys.getenv("CENSUS_API_KEY"))
#head(baltimore)

  • We can quickly turn into a plot

    baltimore %>% 
ggplot(aes(fill = estimate)) + 
  geom_sf(color = NA) + 
  coord_sf(crs = 26911) + 
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "magma")

3.3 Faceted Mapping

  • ggplot2’s support for small multiples works very well with the tidy data format returned by tidycensus.
  • Many Census and ACS variables return counts, which are generally inappropriate for choropleth mapping.
  • However, get_decennial() and get_acs() have an optional argument, summary_var, that can work as a multi-group denominator.

3.3.1 Example of Racial Data

  • Let’s get data for non-Hispanic whites, non-Hispanic blacks, non-Hispanic Asians, and Hispanics by Census tract for the 2010 Census, and specify total population as the summary variable. year is not necessary here as the default is 2010.

    racevars <- c(White = "P005003", 
              Black = "P005004", 
              Asian = "P005006", 
              Hispanic = "P004003")
baltimore_race <- get_decennial(state = "MD", county = "Baltimore City", 
                                geography = "tract", 
                                variables = racevars, geometry = TRUE, 
                                summary_var = "P001001",
                                key = Sys.getenv("CENSUS_API_KEY"))
#head(baltimore_race)

  • Plot percent by Tract

    baltimore_race %>%
  mutate(pct = 100 * (value / summary_value)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = pct)) +
  facet_wrap(~variable) +
  geom_sf(color = NA) +
  coord_sf(crs = 26915) + 
  scale_fill_viridis_c()

4 Go interactive in HTML with the mapview package

  • Allows you to interact with scroll, and zoom

    library(mapview)
mapview(baltimore, zcol = "estimate")

4.1 DC Example with External (Non-Census) Data

  • Download the median house hold income for DC at the census tract level with geography objects

  • Add an explicit variable for CENSUS_TRACT from the GEOID

    dc_median <- get_acs(state = "DC", county = "District of Columbia", geography = "tract", 
                  variables = "B19013_001", geometry = TRUE, key = Sys.getenv("CENSUS_API_KEY"))
dc_median %>% 
  mutate(CENSUS_TRACT = str_sub(GEOID,6,11)) ->
  dc_median
#head(dc_median)

4.1.1 Plot the median household income

  • Variable is estimate

    dc_median %>% 
ggplot(aes(fill = estimate)) +
    geom_sf(aes(geometry = geometry),color = NA) +
    coord_sf(crs = 26915) + 
    scale_fill_viridis_c()

4.1.2 Get an External Crime data

  • Use saved CSV form DC open Data

    crime <- read_csv("./data/dc-crimes-search-results.csv", col_types = cols(DISTRICT = col_factor(),
                                                                         WARD = col_factor(),
                                                                         PSA = col_factor(),
                                                                         METHOD= col_factor()
                                                                         ))

    4.1.2 Plot Crimes by Census Tract

  • Note have to explicitly identify the geometry given the join

    crime %>% 
  filter(METHOD != "others") %>% 
  group_by(CENSUS_TRACT, METHOD) %>%
  count() %>% 
  left_join(dc_median) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(fill = n)) +
    geom_sf(aes(geometry = geometry),color = NA) +
    coord_sf(crs = 26915) + 
    scale_fill_viridis_c() +
    facet_wrap(~METHOD) 
    ## Joining, by = "CENSUS_TRACT"

4.2 Now Get Shape Files for the Wards

  • Download from DC open data for the wards
  • Unzip in a directory

  • Use the sf package function read_sf() to load using the directory name (not a file name)

    wards <- read_sf("./data/Ward_from_2012")
wards %>% 
  mutate(WARD = parse_factor(as.character(WARD))) ->
  wards
   # head(wards)

  • Now plot at the Ward Level

    crime %>% 
  filter(METHOD != "others") %>% 
  group_by(WARD, METHOD) %>%
  count() %>% 
  left_join(wards) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(fill = n)) +
    geom_sf(aes(geometry = geometry),color = NA) +
    coord_sf(crs = 26915) + 
    scale_fill_viridis_c() +
    facet_wrap(~METHOD) 
    ## Joining, by = "WARD"
    ## Warning: Column `WARD` joining factors with different levels, coercing to
## character vector

  • Compare totals by ward

    crime %>% 
  filter(METHOD != "others") %>% 
  group_by(WARD, METHOD) %>%
  count() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = WARD, y = n, color = METHOD)) +
  geom_point()

  • Some wards have more than one census district so the census data does not exactly line up but you could approximate

    crime %>% 
  select(CENSUS_TRACT, WARD) %>% 
  group_by(CENSUS_TRACT) %>% 
  unique() %>% 
  count() %>% 
  filter(n>1) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))

4.3 Add Points of interest to the maps

  • Get and set the lat long for AU as a sf object

    au_latlong <- data.frame(longitude = -77.0888, latitude = 38.9375)
au_latlong<- st_as_sf(au_latlong, coords = c("longitude", "latitude"), 
    crs = 4326, agr = "constant")

  • Add to the crime plot

    crime %>% 
  filter(METHOD != "others") %>% 
  group_by(WARD, METHOD) %>%
  count() %>% 
  left_join(wards) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(fill = n)) +
    geom_sf(aes(geometry = geometry),color = NA) +
    coord_sf(crs = 26915) + 
    scale_fill_viridis_c() +
    facet_wrap(~METHOD) +
   geom_sf(data = au_latlong, size = 4, shape = 23, fill = "red")
    ## Joining, by = "WARD"
    ## Warning: Column `WARD` joining factors with different levels, coercing to
## character vector
    ## Coordinate system already present. Adding new coordinate system, which will replace the existing one.

  • Add to the median household income plot

    dc_median %>% 
ggplot(aes(fill = estimate)) +
    geom_sf(aes(geometry = geometry),color = NA) +
